<section xml:id="Elementary_Matrices">
  <title>Elementary Matrices</title>
  <definition>
    <statement>
      <p>
        An <term>elementary matrix</term>
        is a matrix that when multiplied on the left of a given matrix performs one of the 3 elementary row operations for reducing a matrix.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Find <m>3 \times 3</m> elementary matrices <c>E</c> that do the following actions.
        For each, also find det(<c>E</c>) and <m>\mtx{E}^{-1}</m>.
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              uad \= switch rows 1 and 3
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              multiply row 3 by the number 5
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              add 10 times row 2 to row 3
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Compute determinants for the following matrices.
        Also find the elementary matrices indicated and their determinant.
        Choose carefully how to compute each determinant.
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              uad \= <c>A</c> = <m>\left[ \begin{array}{rrr}-1\amp 2\amp 3\\4\amp 5\amp 6\\7\amp 8\amp 9 \end{array} \right]</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\mtx{E}_1\mtx{A} = \left[ \begin{array}{rrr}4\amp 5\amp 6\\-1\amp 2\amp 3\\7\amp 8\amp 9 \end{array} \right]</m> \= where <m>\mtx{E}_1 =</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\mtx{E}_2\mtx{A} = \left[ \begin{array}{rrr}-10\amp 20\amp 30\\4\amp 5\amp 6\\7\amp 8\amp 9 \end{array} \right]</m> \> where <m>\mtx{E}_2 =</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\mtx{B} = \left[ \begin{array}{rrr}-1\amp 2\amp 3\\-1\amp 2\amp 3\\7\amp 8\amp 9 \end{array} \right]</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\mtx{E}_3\mtx{A} = \left[ \begin{array}{ccc}-1\amp 2\amp 3\\4+-1\amp 5+2\amp 6+3\\7\amp 8\amp 9 \end{array} \right]</m> \> where <m>\mtx{E}_3 =</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\mtx{C} = \left[ \begin{array}{rrr}-1\amp 2\amp 3\\4\amp 5\amp 6\\0\amp 0\amp 0 \end{array} \right]</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\mtx{A}^T = \left[ \begin{array}{rrr}-1\amp 4\amp 7\\2\amp 5\amp 8\\3\amp 6\amp 9 \end{array} \right]</m> (This is called the transpose of <c>A</c>)
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        <term>(Elementary Matrix Lemma)</term>
        For any <m>n \times n</m> matrix <c>M</c> and any
        <m>n \times n</m> elementary matrix <c>E</c>,
        find a relationship between det(<c>EM</c>), det(<c>E</c>) and det(<c>M</c>) .
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <theorem>
    <statement>
      <p>
        For any two <m>n \times n</m> matrices <c>A</c> and <c>B</c>:
        <me>
          det(\mtx{AB})= det(\mtx{A})det(\mtx{B})
        </me>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </theorem>
  <aside>
    <p>
      The key to proving this theorem is to use that <c>A</c> can be reduced using a series of elementary operations to its most simplified form.
      This results in a matrix equation that can be used to write <c>A</c> as a product of elementary matrices followed by either the identity matrix or a matrix having a row of zeros.
      Using the observation made in exercise 25(c) which I called the Elementary Matrix Lemma will finish the proof.
    </p>
  </aside>
</section>